  <article class="prose">
    <h1>RevEmo</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Revenue per Emotional Moment</p>
    <p class="meta">
      Version 1.0 · Published 19 May 2026 · Last updated 19 May 2026 · Status: working paper, under review at <em>International Journal of Hospitality Management</em> · Canonical URL: optimisationblindness.org/revemo
    </p>

    <p>A measurement framework for the economic value of emotional moments in hospitality service encounters.</p>

    <h2>What it measures</h2>

    <p>RevEmo operates at the scale of the property and the individual guest encounter. It quantifies the impact of specific emotional moments — moments in which a guest's affective state shifts measurably during a service interaction — on three downstream economic outcomes: revenue uplift during the current stay, retention through repeat visitation and lifetime value, and the asset valuation of the property over time.</p>

    <p>The framework treats emotional moments as units of analysis. A moment is identifiable, locatable in time and space within the property, and bounded by observable changes in guest behaviour. The questions RevEmo addresses are operational. Which moments produce the largest economic uplift? Which produce no uplift despite consuming operational resources? Which produce negative effects that conventional service-quality instruments fail to detect? Which staff interactions, design choices, or service flows reliably produce moments worth investing in?</p>

    <p>Conventional service-quality measurement aggregates across the stay. It produces satisfaction scores, NPS values, and review averages. These are useful but coarse. They cannot identify the specific moments in which value is created or lost, and they cannot answer the question of which operational investments will produce the largest emotional and economic return. RevEmo is intended as a higher-resolution instrument for that purpose.</p>

    <h2>Scale and unit of analysis</h2>

    <p>RevEmo operates at the property level. The unit of analysis is the guest encounter within a single property over the duration of a stay. The framework can be aggregated across stays for retention and asset-valuation analysis, but the underlying measurement is encounter-level.</p>

    <p>This distinguishes RevEmo from <a href="/deqi">DEQI</a>, which operates at the destination level and measures aggregate effects across multiple properties, platforms, and infrastructures within a tourism city. The two frameworks are complementary. RevEmo is what an operator uses to manage a property. DEQI is what a destination authority uses to manage a city.</p>

    <h2>Relationship to optimisation blindness</h2>

    <p>RevEmo is the property-level operationalisation of the broader <a href="/concept">optimisation blindness</a> concept. Most hospitality optimisation systems — revenue management, channel management, operational dashboards, guest-relationship platforms — optimise for measurable signals that occur after a guest has already decided to engage. RevEmo identifies the emotional moments that produce or destroy the decision to engage in the first place, and that determine whether a guest returns. These moments are systematically invisible to conventional optimisation. RevEmo makes them visible.</p>

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <p>RevEmo is currently in academic review at the <em>International Journal of Hospitality Management</em>. The full mathematical specification, measurement protocols, and empirical validation strategy will be available with the published paper. A working paper version will be posted to a preprint server upon journal acceptance.</p>

